After wrecking Roger Federer’s return to the tennis courts, Pablo Andujar said it was the sweetest moment of a lengthy career. The Spaniard beat Federer 6-4, 4-6, 6-4 on the Geneva clay on Tuesday to overturn the Swiss tennis great’s hopes of stringing a run of matches together ahead of a series of major tournaments – the French Open, Wimbledon and the Tokyo Olympics. At match point on Tuesday, Andujar, the world number 75, held his head in his hands in disbelief after beating the 20-time Grand Slam champion. “It’s amazing. I still cannot believe,” the 35-year-old told ATPTour.com.